var decimalValue = num3.DecimalValue; // 277

members.member:

    Implements running values.




        So-called "running values" are values which are calculated based on a history of previous values.
        The history of previous values has a certain size (or capacity) and all values in that history are used to calculate the running values.



        The number of values in the history () starts at zero.
        It is increased with each added value, but does not exceed .
        When a new value is added and the history already contains  number of values, the oldest value is removed from the history and does no longer contribute to the calculation of the running values.



         is useful in scenarios where performance is critical and a stable algorithmic complexity of approximately O(1) is required, regardless of the size of the history.
        Use  if a higher precision or more calculated values are required (but unfortunately with worse performance).



         can be used for discrete or continuous running values.
        Their usage can be mixed, using  or  with a timestep of 1.0f for discrete values or  for continuous values.
        The running values are always calculated using the weighted value, which is the value multiplied with the corresponding timestep.



